            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Why Overseas Teams Need a Compliance Audit SOP</h2>
<p>Overseas advertising platforms are becoming increasingly strict with violations. A single creative violation can lead to account suspension, costing not just current budget but also missing critical marketing windows.</p>
<p>Many teams wait until accounts are suspended before taking action, which is often too late. Establishing a proactive compliance audit mechanism is the most cost-effective preventive measure.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Ad Account Compliance Audit SOP</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Account Status Check</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Daily</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Log in to the ad dashboard and confirm account status is "Active"</li>
<li>[ ] Verify account balance is sufficient to avoid campaign interruption</li>
<li>[ ] Confirm the primary payment method is valid with adequate credit</li>
<li>[ ] Check for platform violation notifications or warning emails</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Warning Signs</strong>: If you notice unusual login records or permission changes, immediately update passwords and enable two-factor authentication.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h3>Step 2: Creative Compliance Review</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Required before every new creative launches</strong></p>
<p>Before submitting creatives, verify each item:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Does the creative contain exaggerated or false effect claims (e.g., "100% effective," "guaranteed cure")</li>
<li>[ ] Are there face authorization documents for any person images or compliance with local regulations</li>
<li>[ ] Are competitor brand logos or trademarks appearing in the creative</li>
<li>[ ] Are promotional terms clearly labeled with "limited time" or "limited quantity" disclaimers</li>
<li>[ ] Have cultural taboo elements for target markets been checked (religious symbols, color meanings)</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 3: Copy Content Compliance Review</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Required before every ad copy is published</strong></p>
<p>Copy is the most common violation trigger:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Does it use absolute language ("best," "#1," "only")</li>
<li>[ ] Are promise claims consistent with actual product features</li>
<li>[ ] Are price details including complete tax and fee information disclosed</li>
<li>[ ] Is privacy policy link included in the ad</li>
<li>[ ] Has target market language been reviewed by native speakers</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 4: Targeting Compliance Confirmation</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Required when creating or modifying every campaign</strong></p>
<p>Improper targeting can also cause compliance issues:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Does age targeting exclude minors (for specific categories)</li>
<li>[ ] Does geographic targeting comply with local data regulations</li>
<li>[ ] Does interest targeting avoid discriminatory implications</li>
<li>[ ] Does remarketing audience exclude users who explicitly opted out</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 5: Landing Page Compliance Check</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Required when changing landing pages</strong></p>
<p>Even compliant creatives can be rejected due to landing page issues:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Is landing page content consistent with ad promises</li>
<li>[ ] Does the purchase/registration flow include clear unsubscribe options</li>
<li>[ ] Do cookie popups comply with GDPR and other regulations</li>
<li>[ ] Is contact information and company details verifiable</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 6: Budget and Bidding Compliance</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Weekly regular check</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Is daily budget within platform limits</li>
<li>[ ] Are there unusual bidding fluctuations (may trigger platform risk controls)</li>
<li>[ ] Is conversion tracking code functioning properly</li>
<li>[ ] Do attribution windows match business objectives</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 7: Payment and Financial Reconciliation</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Weekly financial reconciliation</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Do ad spend amounts match account charges</li>
<li>[ ] Are top-up records complete and traceable</li>
<li>[ ] Are there any unauthorized charges</li>
<li>[ ] For multi-account management, are each account's expenses clearly separated</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 8: Competitor and Copyright Check</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: Monthly comprehensive review</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Does the creative involve unauthorized music, video, or images</li>
<li>[ ] Does trending marketing infringe on others' copyrights or trademarks</li>
<li>[ ] Are user-generated content (UGC) properly authorized</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 9: Compliance Training Updates</h3>
<p><strong>Frequency: When team members change or policies update</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Have team members completed the latest platform policy training</li>
<li>[ ] Has special compliance training been conducted before entering new markets</li>
<li>[ ] Have historical violation cases been compiled into internal learning materials</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Step 10: Rapid Response to Anomalies</h3>
<p><strong>Trigger: When discovering account anomalies or receiving platform notices</strong></p>
<p>If any of the following occur, initiate emergency response immediately:</p>
<ol>
<li>Unauthorized account login → Immediately change password, freeze account</li>
<li>Platform violation notice received → Prepare appeal materials within 24 hours</li>
<li>Abnormal spending spike → Pause all ads and investigate</li>
<li>Creative rejected → Analyze rejection reason, revise and resubmit</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Compliance Audit Execution Recommendations</h2>
<p><strong>Tool Support</strong>: Use spreadsheets or project management tools to record each audit result, creating traceable compliance logs.</p>
<p><strong>Responsibility Division</strong>: Medium-sized teams can assign a dedicated compliance role; smaller teams should designate at least one person as compliance lead.</p>
<p><strong>Regular Reviews</strong>: Compile monthly summaries of violation cases and audit findings to update internal compliance checklists.</p>
<hr />
<p>Compliance is not a one-time task but a daily mechanism that requires consistent execution. Turning this checklist into a team work habit is much easier than remediation after violations occur.</p>
